<ArticleLayout title="Five grid connection risks to address early" category="Project strategy" readTime="5 min read" description="Five common grid connection risks that renewable energy project teams should address early.">
<p class="lead">Grid connection risk is rarely isolated to the connection workstream. It can affect equipment procurement, project schedule, financing assumptions and even the commercial viability of the project.</p>
<h2>1. Unclear network constraints</h2><p>Connection point strength, congestion, planned network changes and neighbouring projects can materially change the study outcome. Establish the network context early and keep it current.</p>
<h2>2. Misaligned models and design</h2><p>Studies are only useful when model assumptions reflect the intended plant. Poor alignment between OEM models, electrical design and control settings often leads to repeated analysis.</p>
<h2>3. Late OEM engagement</h2><p>Key compliance outcomes can depend on inverter or turbine controls. Early OEM ownership of model quality, parameter limits and tuning expectations reduces programme risk.</p>
<h2>4. Weak interface management</h2><p>Grid connection crosses multiple technical and organisational boundaries. Define responsibilities, information flows and decision authority clearly.</p>
<h2>5. Underestimating R1 and R2</h2><p>Registration and commissioning evidence should be planned during the application stage. A project that treats R1 and R2 as future activities can discover costly gaps too late.</p>
</ArticleLayout>
